1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:02,488
Codex became too useful for me to stop using.

2
00:00:02,488 --> 00:00:11,659
But as my projects grew, a single task could take more than an hour, repeatedly scanning the same repository and consuming an unreasonable amount of context.

3
00:00:11,659 --> 00:00:18,306
I built Vertex Palace around one practical question: can an agent receive the right context without reading everything?

4
00:00:18,960 --> 00:00:25,989
The inspiration came from turning flat, two-dimensional repository data into a navigable, three-dimensional memory palace.

5
00:00:25,989 --> 00:00:32,410
Directory location becomes the X axis, business function the Y axis, and dependencies the Z axis.

6
00:00:32,410 --> 00:00:40,148
Domains become floors, functional areas become rooms, and files, symbols, tests, and memories become drawers.

7
00:00:40,148 --> 00:00:45,546
For each task, Palace plans a route and delivers a small, explainable context pack.

8
00:00:46,198 --> 00:00:50,511
But a shorter route is only a hypothesis, so I designed a public research process.

9
00:00:50,511 --> 00:00:58,795
I used Codex with G P T five point six to build the command-line interface, M C P server, plugin, tests, and benchmark harness.

10
00:00:58,795 --> 00:01:05,886
Then I froze protocols before results, preserved failed runs, found mechanisms, changed the product, and tested again.

11
00:01:06,565 --> 00:01:10,355
In the first formal study, sixty out of sixty agent arms were correct.

12
00:01:10,355 --> 00:01:14,640
Full Palace also rejected stale memory in every stale-memory run.

13
00:01:14,640 --> 00:01:24,435
But compared with Control, it used a median sixty-seven thousand two hundred twenty-three more reported tokens, eight point five more tool calls, and about thirty extra seconds.

14
00:01:24,435 --> 00:01:29,526
The first conclusion was uncomfortable but useful: Palace was safe, but too heavy.

15
00:01:30,179 --> 00:01:35,958
Study two introduced Adaptive Palace, choosing among route-lite, full context, and guarded memory.

16
00:01:35,958 --> 00:01:38,492
All sixty-four arms were valid and correct.

17
00:01:38,492 --> 00:01:45,435
Adaptive reduced Palace's own output, but it still did not prove a universal end-to-end advantage over pure Codex.

18
00:01:45,435 --> 00:01:52,492
More importantly, the study exposed a memory-fidelity bug: required useful memories were missed in four out of four cases.

19
00:01:52,492 --> 00:01:54,026
We published that failure too.

20
00:01:54,681 --> 00:01:57,574
That negative result changed the engineering direction.

21
00:01:57,574 --> 00:02:09,506
Generation three focuses on causes: true bypass for simple tasks, complete and explainable memory selection, stop conditions that limit unnecessary exploration, and stronger type and task-intent routing.

22
00:02:09,506 --> 00:02:19,085
Validation is expanding to real issues, real Git commits, real tests, TypeScript and Python repositories, hidden oracles, and public failure records.

23
00:02:19,085 --> 00:02:24,608
Correctness comes first, modification scope second, and token efficiency only after both.

24
00:02:24,608 --> 00:02:30,903
The new question is whether Adaptive Palace can beat pure Codex without hiding information or weakening correctness.

25
00:02:31,581 --> 00:02:35,769
Vertex Palace is open source, and the benchmark process is public.

26
00:02:35,769 --> 00:02:40,996
Visit the product repository for source code, architecture, releases, and installation.

27
00:02:40,996 --> 00:02:47,428
Visit the research repository for protocols, raw trials, negative results, and reproducible evidence.

28
00:02:47,428 --> 00:02:48,099
Build it.

29
00:02:48,099 --> 00:02:48,792
Test it.

30
00:02:48,792 --> 00:02:50,076
Publish the evidence.
